Conversation:
User A: Music Streaming as an Economic Shift (a theory in 8 tweets):

User A: 1/8. Economically speaking, streaming services take a lower cut (~30%) than download stores (~35%) or CD manufacturers/distributors/sellers (~55%), and thus are better for artists (and the rest of the music industry) per $ spent.

User A: 2/8. Streaming is also now producing more total $ than downloads ever did, and is on track to MAYBE generate more inflation-adjusted royalties than CDs within a couple years.

User A: 3/8. Those $, however, are distributed differently across listeners. In the CD era, the highest spenders each controlled $1000s/year of buying. In the streaming era, they control $10/month at most, like anybody else.

User A: 4/8. The argument over pro-rata and user-centric payment models SOUNDS like it's about this, but the (current) pro-rata streaming model is actually biased TOWARDS smaller artists, in practice, by a small (5-10%) amount.

User A: 5/8. The people who listen more, and thus control more $ in the pro-rata model, tend to listen to less popular artists. But in streaming this effect is small, regardless of direction.

-The body tries to eliminates it because it's abnormal and this causes 60% of miscarriages and it's common in older women [URL]

User A: 2. RHESUS FACTOR INCOMPATIBILITY

- When the blood of the mother is Rh-ve and the baby blood is Rh+ve.

- There is a difference in the Rh factor between a mother(-) and the baby(+), the body of the mother recognizes the baby as a foreign body, attacks it and causes a miscarriage. [URL]

User A: 3. HORMONAL IMBALANCE
- Progesterone is the hormone of pregnancy, the hormone that keeps the baby till birth.

- The uterus commonly known as the womb houses the child [URL]

User A: 5. INFECTIONS
- Infections such as Rubella (German Measles), Herpes Simplex, Chlamydia can affect baby growth and cause miscarriage.

- People who smoke weed/tobacco and take alcohol in pregnancy are at risk of having miscarriage because these things affect the child. [URL]

User A: Sometimes it’s hard to explain to people what racism looks & feels like.

What it’s like to walk into a 350 room hotel in Cannes with many (white) people coming/going & be the only person stopped before entering, questioned if I have a room here.
Lemme tell u the feeling sucks

User A: And when I calmly raised my concerns with reception that I have been singled out/profiled because I am not-white, the receptionist doubles down, asks if I AM in fact staying at the hotel, defends the bellman/security, says they don’t know me (but know the 100s they didn’t stop?)

User A: I’ve had a week of nothing but terrific service experiences in France. I am devastated this happened.

User A: When you’re a person of colour, you just know in your bones when you’ve experienced racism, yet it’s hard to prove. You learn to ignore it and deal. But sometimes it just smacks you in the face that you can’t.

User A: And I recognise this racist micro aggression at a stupid luxury hotel is nothing compared to what Black, Indigenous, dark skinned POC experience daily, where jogging, wearing a hoodie, not pulling over fast enough can mean death.

User A: You learn you always have to be presentable so you don’t get singled out. You learn to dress up to do an errand or, say, go to a car dealership. I’ve spent too much time trying to make a good impression just so I won’t be judged. It’s exhausting. And sometimes still doesn’t work.

User A: I generally crave being ignored/unbothered in public. I’m tweeting this to remind myself that it is tied to privilege. Because when you aren’t the dominant caste, they will question your right to be in their space (like a Black man bird watching in Central Park).

User B: @USER Not really helpful (from a relatively rich caucasian living in a relatively free country who is pretty much free to travel the world that is) but there is always someone in a worse position.

User A: @USER You’re right, not really helpful :/

“Keep a stiff upper lip, many have it worse” is something that was ingrained into me by my immigrant parents; it’s the way they survived in a new country. It’s taken years of travel, writing & self exploration to strip that toxic attitude.

User A: Years ago, from an audio standpoint, there weren't many Bucs podcasts around. The pinnacle was WTB, and some kinda came and went. I don't believe credentialed media had figured out the podcast market at the time.

User A: Getting into podcasting should always be about exploring an avenue that you're passionate about. It should never be about downloads. It should never be about getting followers or likes on social media. As a podcaster, you should be able to turn on your mic at any time and just go

User A: I was lucky enough to develop good relationships with some credentialed media folks and a few within the Bucs organization. That's the only reason I was allowed to do some of the content I was able to do. We also seemed to have more of a fellowship.

User A: Some others started seeing the trend of podcasting and got into the game. Most were very professional. I helped a few get theirs going, including 1 who would never actually give someone credit and took the route of trashing folks and talking sh!t. Britney would say it was "toxic"

User A: Only speaking for myself, I gravitated toward the type of work I was doing and the content provided by WTB. No matter what crazy was happening, Old School could spell it out for you in a way that people could easily understand. He inhaled the good sh!t and exhaled the bullsh!t.

User A: The trends of social media and trying to be "louder" than others started a trend of dragging down the fanbase. It wasn't team content any longer. It was "how much Scott Reynolds of PR sucks, or "how biased Tom Jones was and you fans should go threaten them at training camp".

User A: Yeah, I legit heard content in an audio format sent to me that suggested to fans that they should harass media members at Bucs training camp. How did the hosting site of this podcast react? They "aren't responsible for the content".

User A: How did the organization react? Well, Hard Knocks was in town, so let's use it as a way to make us look good as an organization and ignore what was being encouraged. IMO, there should have been ZERO tolerance from the organization on this, but yeah,gotta look good for the cameras

User A: I reacted by blocking those individuals -- those who hosted the content, and those who provided it. Enter a whole slew of new Bucs podcast audio, while in the background, WTB and I are observing what was going on.

User A: And, that content continued to be celebrated. If people wanted to ignore it, they could have, but instead they chose to talk about it, plug it, and allow that ignorance and hate on their own podcasts. Gotta have those clicks and downloads!

User A: I, personally had enough. Too many hours. Too much work. Too many things pulling me away from what was actually important in life, and it wasn't a sport that was important. Sports podcasting is a very interesting topic when it comes to how and who people are invested in.

User A: Fast forward to today. What are we at, 74 Bucs podcasts? Not enough hours in the week to even try and listen. For some, the trend may have become - "let's talk about what Rick Stroud said" or, "did you read that Jenna Laine story?" versus - "Here are my opinions and this is why."

User A: I actually thought when the toxic individual went away, the atmosphere would improve. Maybe it was just always this bad? What we see today is a trend of petty and childish bickering between "some" of the folks who are paid to provide content to fans.
